1. do you include all the hostnames in the SAN field? I saw some email chain that said include hostname B and C and the SAN field and hostname A in the subject DN. This will fail with RFC 2818. Hostnames A, B and C must all be included in SAN and one of them can be repeated in the subject name.
2.  You should get confirmation from JIm, but I think you will need to pass the email address. We put this in our CP/CPS as a requirement.

Mine Altunay</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='27445#1447968763'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2015-11-19T21:32:43+00:00">Nov 19, 2015 09:32 PM UTC</time> by <b>Soichi Hayashi</b><a class="anchor" name="1447968763">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Jim,

I&#39;ve updated OIM to parse the input CSR and apply the same GridAdmin domain validations currently applied to CNs on specified SANs.  I&#39;ve tested it by configuring my test OIM instance to send request to osg0.cilogon.org.

CILogon was able to issue a cert with all SANs I have listed via alt_hostnames parameter.

<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; X509v3 Subject Alternative Name&#58;</font>
<font color='#7F7E6F'>&#62; DNS&#58;soichi.grid.iu.edu, DNS&#58;san1.grid.iu.edu, DNS&#58;san2.grid.iu.edu, DNS&#58;san3.grid.iu.edu, email&#58;noemail@....</font>

Currently, HSM seems to be requiring email address specified (I&#39;ve set it to noemail@....) in above sample. OIM currently does not set email address for Digicert issued host certificate. Can this requirement removed, or do I need to update to pass issuer&#39;s email address?

Soichi</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='27445#1447954124'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2015-11-19T17:28:44+00:00">Nov 19, 2015 05:28 PM UTC</time><a class="anchor" name="1447954124">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>The test endpoints at <a href='https&#58;//osg0.cilogon.org/getservicecert' target='_blank' rel='nofollow'>https&#58;//osg0.cilogon.org/getservicecert</a> and <a href='https&#58;//osg0.cilogon.org/gethostcert' target='_blank' rel='nofollow'>https&#58;//osg0.cilogon.org/gethostcert</a> now support the alt_hostnames parameter and are ready for testing by OSG. We will not deploy this change to the production endpoints (<a href='https&#58;//osg.cilogon.org/getservicecert' target='_blank' rel='nofollow'>https&#58;//osg.cilogon.org/getservicecert</a> and <a href='https&#58;//osg.cilogon.org/gethostcert' target='_blank' rel='nofollow'>https&#58;//osg.cilogon.org/gethostcert</a>) until OSG approves.

by /DC=org/DC=cilogon/C=US/O=University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign/CN=James Basney A534</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='27445#1447793948'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2015-11-17T20:59:08+00:00">Nov 17, 2015 08:59 PM UTC</time> by <b>Mine Altunay</b><a class="anchor" name="1447793948">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Security team agrees with this change. But, following our process, I would like Soichi as a representative of operations to also chime in. We should also make a change to our domain vetting process that we can accomodate multiple FQDNs.</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='27445#1447778130'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2015-11-17T16:35:30+00:00">Nov 17, 2015 04:35 PM UTC</time><a class="anchor" name="1447778130">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>To satisfy this request, we propose to add a new optional alt_hostnames parameter to the <a href='https&#58;//osg.cilogon.org/getservicecert' target='_blank' rel='nofollow'>https&#58;//osg.cilogon.org/getservicecert</a> and <a href='https&#58;//osg.cilogon.org/gethostcert' target='_blank' rel='nofollow'>https&#58;//osg.cilogon.org/gethostcert</a> endpoints for specifying additional fully-qualified hostnames to include in the certificate subjectAltName. I&#39;ve updated <a href='https&#58;//goo.gl/pxDrsp' target='_blank' rel='nofollow'>https&#58;//goo.gl/pxDrsp</a> with the proposed API change. As always, CILogon relies on OSG to properly vet all hostnames to be included in the certificate. If you agree, we&#39;ll first make the change on a test instance at <a href='https&#58;//osg0.cilogon.org/getservicecert' target='_blank' rel='nofollow'>https&#58;//osg0.cilogon.org/getservicecert</a> and <a href='https&#58;//osg0.cilogon.org/gethostcert' target='_blank' rel='nofollow'>https&#58;//osg0.cilogon.org/gethostcert</a> and wait for your approval before deploying to production.

by /DC=org/DC=cilogon/C=US/O=University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign/CN=James Basney A534</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='27445#1447709696'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2015-11-16T21:34:56+00:00">Nov 16, 2015 09:34 PM UTC</time> by <b>Mine Altunay</b><a class="anchor" name="1447709696">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>The OSG Security team requests a change to the CIlogon OSG CA. Currently, this CA can only provide a single FQDN in the Subject Alternative Name (SAN) field of a certificate. We are requesting to have the ability to have multiple FQDNs included in the SAN field. This request stems from the recent changes planned to the Globus API (which is moving to implement a strict definition of RFC 2818) and the needs of some of the OSG sites (which need support for multiple FQDN values). The request will require changes to the CILogon HSM backend and to the OIM APIs which need to pass on multiple FQDNs to CILogon HSM service.</pre></div><legend>Similar Recent Tickets <small>modified within the last 30 days</small></legend><div id="similar_tickets"><p class="muted">No similar tickets found.</p></div>
